  "prompt": "Why did oil prices fall again in 2015?",
  "response": "Oil prices fell in 2015 due to a combination of factors:\n\n1. **Increased Supply**: The United States saw a significant increase in oil production, primarily due to the shale oil boom. This contributed to a global surplus of oil.\n\n2. **OPEC's Policy**: The Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), particularly Saudi Arabia, chose not to cut production to stabilize prices. Their strategy was aimed at maintaining market share and putting pressure on higher-cost producers, such as U.S. shale companies.\n\n3. **Weak Global Demand**: There was weaker-than-expected global economic growth, which reduced the demand for oil. Key economies, such as China and parts of Europe, were experiencing slowdowns, further dampening demand.\n\n4. **Strong U.S. Dollar**: Oil is priced in U.S. dollars, and a stronger dollar makes oil more expensive for other countries to purchase, which can lead to reduced demand.\n\n5. **Geopolitical Stability**: Despite ongoing tensions in various oil-producing regions, there were no significant disruptions to supply at the time, which kept the market well-supplied.\n\nThese factors combined to create an oversupplied market, leading to a significant decline in oil prices throughout 2014 and into 2015.",
